ulo pipeline is the latest attempt to solve the problem of access of the resources of Bolivia's Oriente to world markets. Both Brazil and Bolivia are countries where, for centuries, weak central governments sought to develop and manage large parts of the 
South American heartland with low population densities. Bolivia's defeats have been dramatic. It lost large slices of its original territory to its neighbors. Throughout its history, Bolivia has been plagued by problems of space, population density and co
mmunications, again and again threatening its survival as a national state. Its past role in the world economy might have promised some success in overcoming difficulties like these. In the 17th Century silver mining complex of Potos\'92
, Bolivia, harbored the biggest and richest export enclave of the preindustrial West and the largest urban concentration in the New World (120,000 population by 1610, against 200,000 for London around the same time). Mining at Potos\'92
 was supported by an extensive system of draft labor and food and materials supply, extending over much of what is now the north of Argentina and the highlands and valleys of Peru and Bolivia. Nevertheless, following collapse of the Potos\'92
 mining boom, internal communications had deteriorated so badly
 that a British diplomat reported in 1827: "the roads throughout Bolivia are only adapted for mules and llamas --a cart or carriage road does not exist in any part of the Republic, and with the exception of one or two carriages used in religious ceremonie
s at Chuquisaca (Sucre), a wheeled vehicle does not exist in any part of Bolivia."}{\cs16\super \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\f12\fs20\lang1046\langfe1046\cgrid\langnp1046\langfenp1046 {\cs16\super \chftn }{\f40 . J.B. Pentland, quoted in J. Valerie Fifer , }{\i\f40 Bolivia: Land Location and Politics since 1825.}{\f40  Cambridge University Press, 1972, p. 18.}}}{
\b0\f40\ulnone  Sim\'97n Bol\'92var, whose name the new republic bore, questioned its viability soon after it declared Independence in 1825: "Bolivia cannot remain as she is, because the R\'92
o de la Plata and the Emperor of Brazil would eventually bring about the destruction of that Republic."}{\cs16\super \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\f12\fs20\lang1046\langfe1046\cgrid\langnp1046\langfenp1046 {\cs16\super \chftn }{\f40 . J. Valerie Fifer, }{\i\f40 Bolivia: Land Location and Politics since 1825.}{\f40  Cambridge University Press, 1972 p16. }}}{\b0\f40\ulnone 
 Despite such catastrophic predictions, repeated many times, despite poverty and illiteracy and hundreds of episodes of political disorder, Bolivians developed
 a surprisingly strong sense of national cohesion and identity. In the absence of alternative opportunities, development of this cohesion and identity accelerated in the postwar decades, fed by migrations, racial mixing and large amounts of foreign aid in
 Bolivia's Oriente, the main source of gas supplies for the pipeline to S\'8b
o Paulo. The city of Santa Cruz has grown since 1950 at an astonishing rate, by nearly 7% yearly, to reach a 1992 population of 695,000, with migrants of highland Amerindian descent }{\b0\i\f40\ulnone (kollas) }{\b0\f40\ulnone 
now outnumbering native lowlanders }{\b0\i\f40\ulnone (kambas).}{\b0\f40\ulnone . 
\par This is a sudden awakening from stagnation. Since the 16th Century, bands of white men and }{\b0\i\f40\ulnone mestizos}{\b0\f40\ulnone 
  roamed the vast and trackless frontier east of the Andes to form isolated and often ephemeral settlements. Santa Cruz de la Sierra, at the western hub of the proposed pipeline, was founded by the Spanish conqueror \'84uflo de Ch\'87
vez in 1560, 200 miles east of its present location. The old site soon was abandoned because of Indian attacks. The town grew to 9
,000 population in 1825 and expanded slowly to reach 25,000 a century later and 41,000 by 1950. The region suffered big losses of population in the Chaco War. However, from the ashes of this conflict came the oil-for-railways agreements with Argentina and
 Brazil , a big step toward overcoming the historic problem of access. 
